  "opinion": "As a woman in my sixties who’s spent decades working as an electrician in Philadelphia, I’ve seen firsthand how the gender gap in science isn’t just a statistic—it’s a lived reality. My own journey started in a world where women were rarely encouraged to pursue technical fields, and even today, when I talk to young girls about careers, I hear the same hesitations: ‘Can I really do this?’ or ‘It’s not for me.’ The gap isn’t just about numbers—it’s about the invisible barriers that make women feel like they don’t belong in labs, engineering classrooms, or even basic technical trades. My parents, both educated, taught me that science was for everyone, but the system often ignores that message. I’ve seen it in my own community: too few women in STEM fields, even in trades like electrical work where I’ve built my life. The gap should be addressed because it’s not just about fairness—it’s about the future of our communities. We need to create spaces where girls and women feel safe to explore their curiosity, whether they’re building circuits or studying complex systems. For me, this means mentoring programs that start early, partnerships with schools to make science feel accessible, and leadership roles for women in technical fields. It’s not about changing the system overnight, but about nurturing the next generation with the confidence they deserve. I’ve always believed in the power of hands-on learning, and that’s what I’ll keep advocating for—because when girls see women succeeding in science, they’ll believe they can too.",
